This page gives you guidance on how to stay safely in the Cayman Islands as a visitor, if you are unable to Return to the UK.
Everyone should comply with the measures put in place in the Cayman Islands to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
Moving around in the Cayman Islands
Inter-Island flights will continue; however, flights from Grand Cayman into Cayman Brac and Little Cayman will be restricted to residents and essential persons, for example, medical staff. See further information on Entry requirements.
The Cayman Islands has implemented shelter-in-place regulations which restrict travel to public places (supermarkets, banks etc) between 5am and 7pm, and restricts all movement between 7pm and 5am except for essential workers.
There is a ban on public meetings and gatherings of two people or more until further notice. This ban excludes premises such as hospitals, pharmacies and supermarkets. The fine for breaching the ban on public gatherings is CI$1,000 or up to 6 months imprisonment.
Workplaces, unless they have been designated as essential public places or provide essential services, are closed.
Restaurants are open for curbside pick-up, drive-through delivery only. Bars, spas, gyms, hairdressers, public and private strata swimming pools are also closed. The bus service has been suspended and taxis are limited to 2 passengers only.
Educational facilities will remain closed for the rest of the academic year.
Health
Your emotional and mental wellbeing is important. Read guidance on how to look after your mental wellbeing and mental health.
View Health for further details on healthcare in the Cayman Islands.
